To quickly and significantly adjust the AutoLion battery capacity to match the experimental value when there is a mismatch, follow these steps:

---

### ✅ **Step-by-Step Solution:**

#### 1. **Identify the Mismatch**
- Open the **"Voltage" monitor** in GT-POST.
- Compare the **AutoLion voltage curve** with the **experimental voltage curve**.
- Observe where the **capacity** of the AutoLion model is **not matching** the experimental data.

---

#### 2. **Adjust the Cathode Capacity Loading**
- **Go to the AutoLion part** in GT-ISE.
- Navigate to the **"Cathode" folder**.
- Locate the **"Capacity Loading" attribute**.
- **Change the value** of this attribute to match the **experimental capacity**.

#### 3. **Use the Design Optimizer for Fine-Tuning**
- Open the **Design Optimizer** from the toolbar.
- Set up an **optimization routine** to minimize the **root-mean-square (RMS) error** between the **AutoLion voltage** and the **experimental voltage**.
- Include the following **parameters** in the optimization:
  - **Cathode Capacity Loading**
  - **Anode Capacity Loading**
  - **N/P Ratio**
  - **Initial SOC**
  - **Other relevant parameters** (e.g., particle size, thickness, etc.)

#### 4. **Run the Optimization**
- Set the **objective** to **minimize the RMS error**.
- Run the **optimization** and let it converge to the best fit.
- The optimizer will automatically adjust the parameters to bring the **AutoLion voltage** closer to the **experimental data**.

---

### ✅ **Why This Works:**
- The **capacity loading** directly affects the **total capacity** of the cell.
- By adjusting the **capacity loading**, you can **quickly align** the **AutoLion model** with the **experimental capacity**.
- The **Design Optimizer** allows for **systematic fine-tuning** of multiple parameters to achieve a **highly accurate match**.

---

### ✅ **Optional: Use the "Show Preprocess Plot"**
- Double-click on the **AutoLion part** and click **"Show Preprocess Plot"**.
- This will show the **Design Report**, which includes the **operational capacity** of the cell.
- Use this value as a **starting point** for the **capacity loading** parameter.

---

### ✅ **Summary:**
| Step | Action |
|------|--------|
| 1 | Compare AutoLion and experimental voltage curves |
| 2 | Adjust the **Cathode Capacity Loading** to match experimental capacity |
| 3 | Use the **Design Optimizer** to fine-tune other parameters |
| 4 | Run the optimization to minimize RMS error |
| 5 | Verify the match in the **Voltage Monitor** in GT-POST |

---

### ✅ **Final Result:**
After following these steps, the **AutoLion model** should closely match the **experimental capacity** and **voltage behavior**, ensuring accurate simulation results.
